We consider fractional integral operators $(I-T)^d, d \in (-1,1)$ acting on functions $g: \mathbb{Z}^{
u} 	o \mathbb{R}, 
u \ge 1 $, where $T $  is the transition operator of a random walk on 
$\mathbb{Z}^{
u}$. We obtain sufficient and necessary conditions for the existence, invertibility and square summability of kernels $	au (\mathbf{s}; d), \mathmb{s} \in \mathbb{Z}^{
u}$   of $(I-T)^d $. Asymptotic behavior of $	au (\mathbf{s}; d)$ as $|\mathbf{s}| 	o \infty$ is identified following local limit theorem for random walk.
A class of fractionally integrated random fields $X$ on $\mathbb{Z}^{
u}$ solving the difference equation $(I-T)^d X = \varepsilon$ with white noise on the right-hand side is discussed, and their scaling
limits. Several examples  including fractional  lattice Laplace and heat operators are studied in detail.
